1594":"1594","1571":"1571","from 1532 to 1537":"od 1532 do 1537","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1557":"1557","1535":"1535","25 January 1559":"25. ledna 1559","1621":"1621","1587":"1587","1532":"1532","1585":"1585","1530":"1530","17 November 1587":"17. listopadu 1587","31 December 1557":"31. prosince 1557","1506":"1506","1539":"1539","1549":"1549","1559":"1559","Lavenham, Suffolk, England":"Lavenham, Suffolk, Anglie"},"da":{"from 1532 to 1537–17 November 1587":"fra 1532 til 1537–17. november 1587","1530–Female":"1530–Afdød","1532–1587":"1532–1587","1539–Male":"1539–Afdød","1535–1594":"1535–1594","1557–1621":"1557–1621","1559–Male":"1559–Afdød","–Male":"Afdød","1506–1594":"1506–1594","1594":"1594","1571":"1571","from 1532 to 1537":"fra 1532 til 1537","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1557":"1557","1535":"1535","25 January 1559":"25. januar 1559","1621":"1621","1587":"1587","1532":"1532","1585":"1585","1530":"1530","17 November 1587":"17. november 1587","31 December 1557":"31. december 1557","1506":"1506","1539":"1539","1549":"1549","1559":"1559","Lavenham, Suffolk, England":"Lavenham, Suffolk, England"},"nl":{"from 1532 to 1537–17 November 1587":"van 1532 to 1537–17 november 1587","1530–Female":"1530–Overleden","1532–1587":"1532–1587","1539–Male":"1539–Overleden","1535–1594":"1535–1594","1557–1621":"1557–1621","1559–Male":"1559–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1506–1594":"1506–1594","1594":"1594","1571":"1571","from 1532 to 1537":"van 1532 to 1537","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1557":"1557","1535":"1535","25 January 1559":"25 januari 1559","1621":"1621","1587":"1587","1532":"1532","1585":"1585","1530":"1530","17 November 1587":"17 november 1587","31 December 1557":"31 december 1557","1506":"1506","1539":"1539","1549":"1549","1559":"1559","Lavenham, Suffolk, England":"Lavenham, Suffolk, England"},"en":{"from 1532 to 1537–17 November 1587":"from 1532 to 1537–17 November 1587","1530–Female":"1530–Deceased","1532–1587":"1532–1587","1539–Male":"1539–Deceased","1535–1594":"1535–1594","1557–1621":"1557–1621","1559–Male":"1559–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1506–1594":"1506–1594","1594":"1594","1571":"1571","from 1532 to 1537":"from 1532 to 1537","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1557":"1557","1535":"1535","25 January 1559":"25 January 1559","1621":"1621","1587":"1587","1532":"1532","1585":"1585","1530":"1530","17 November 1587":"17 November 1587","31 December 1557":"31 December 1557","1506":"1506","1539":"1539","1549":"1549","1559":"1559","Lavenham, Suffolk, England":"Lavenham, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Payne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Pai(e)n</i>, <i>Pagen</i> (from Latin <i>Paganus</i>), a fairly common personal name among Normans. It derived from a word that originally meant ‘villager, rustic’, later ‘heathen’, but it had doubtless lost these connotations in its use as a late medieval personal name. This name has also been established in Ireland since the 14th century.","History: Thomas Payne, who was a freeman of Plymouth Colony in 1639, was the founder of a large American family, which included Robert Treat Paine (1731–1814), one of the signers of the Declaration of Independence. See also   Paine  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Payn","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Payne  ."]},{"name":"Payen","meanings":["French: from the Old French personal name <i>Pagen</i>, <i>Paien</i>, from Latin <i>Paganus</i>, from <i>paganus</i> ‘country-dweller’, a derivative of <i>pagus</i> ‘of or relating to the countryside’, possibly given to a child not yet baptized (because of its later sense of ‘pagan, heathen’). Alternatively, a nickname for a country-born person. This surname is also found in the West Indies (mainly Haiti) and Mauritius.","English: variant of   Payne  ."]},{"name":"Pagan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Luis, Juan, Angel, Carlos, Rafael, Ramon, Pedro, Francisco, Jesus, Miguel, Julio.","Spanish and Catalan: Castilianized form (<b>Pagán</b>) of Catalan <b>Pagà</b>, from the Late Latin personal name <i>Paganus</i>, which as a derivative of Latin <i>pagus</i> ‘outlying village’ originally meant ‘villager’ (see   Payne  ). Alternatively, in some cases, a topographic name from Catalan <i>pagà</i> ‘heath’ (from the same Latin word <i>pagus</i>).","English: from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Pai(e)n</i>, <i>Pagen</i>, from Late Latin <i>Paganus</i> (see   Payne  , compare 1 above)."]},{"name":"Paynes","meanings":["English: variant of   Payne  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Paine","meanings":["English: variant of   Payne  .","History: The author of the republican treatise <i>The Rights of Man</i>, Thomas Paine (1737–1809), left England for North America in the mid 1770s, where he became involved in the movement that led to independence. His pamphlet of 1776, <i>Common Sense</i>, influenced the Declaration of Independence and furnished some of the arguments justifying it."]},{"name":"Pank","meanings":["English (Norfolk): perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Pank(e)</i>. It could be a shortened form of <i>Pancok</i>, which is probably a pet form of <i>Pane</i> (see   Payne  ).","Sorbian: nickname from a diminutive of <i>pan</i> ‘mister, lord, landlord’ (see   Pan  ). Compare   Panke  ."]},{"name":"Pane","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Antonio, Salvatore, Aldo, Carmela, Carmine, Ciro, Concetta, Enzo, Giuseppe, Mario, Armando, Claudio, Macario, Remigio.","Italian: from <i>pane</i> ‘bread’, used as a metonymic occupational name for a baker or as a nickname meaning ‘good thing’, and also as a personal name. This surname is also found in southern France and Corsica.","English: variant of   Payne  ."]},{"name":"Panes","meanings":["English (Somerset): variant of   Payne  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Pannell","meanings":["English (southeastern):","possibly from Middle English <i>panel</i>, <i>panel(l)e</i> ‘cloth, saddle-cloth, saddle’ or ‘pane (of glass)’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a maker of such items.","from the Middle English personal name <i>Paynel</i> (Old French <i>Payenel</i>, Latin <i>Paganellus</i>), a pet form of   Payne   (from Latin <i>Paganus</i>)."]},{"name":"Penson","meanings":["English:","patronymic from the Middle English female personal name <i>Penn</i>, a pet form of <i>Pernel</i>, or perhaps from the Middle English personal name   Payne   + <i>-son</i>. See   Penn  ,   Parnell  .","habitational name from Penson in North Huish (Devon), which derives from the Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Payn(e)</i> (see   Payne  ) + Middle English <i>toun</i> ‘village, town, settlement’ (Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":17,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":26,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":37,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":39,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":53,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":55,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Payne II was born from 1532 